{{Expand Serbian|Јован Хаџи-Васиљевић|date=July 2015}}
[[File:Јован Хаџи-Васиљевић 1899.jpg|thumb]]

'''Jovan Hadži-Vasiljević''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Јован Хаџи-Васиљевић}}, 18 October 1866 – 29 March 1948) was a Serbian historian, ethnographer, journalist and writer. Hadži-Vasiljević was born in [[Vranje]], at the time part of the [[Sanjak of Niš]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] until it was captured by the [[Serbian-Turkish Wars (1876-1878)|Serbian Army in 1878]]. His father was Hadži Vasilije of the Pogačarević family, and his mother Katerina was the daughter of the churchwarden (''ikonom'') of [[Kumanovo district (Ottoman)|Kumanovo]], [[Dimitrije Mladenović]] (1794–1880).<ref name=biblioteke>{{cite web|title=Dr Jovan Hadži Vasiljević (1866-1948)|publisher=biblioteke.org.rs|url=http://www.biblioteke.org.rs/vranje/jovan.html}} {{better source|date=July 2015}}</ref> The Pogačarević family (also known as ''Pogačarci'') hailed from Rakovac, having settled in Vranje at the end of the 18th century.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jovan Hadži-Vasiljević|title=Južna stara Srbija: istorijska, etnografska i politička istraživanja|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j7FOAQAAIAAJ|year=1913|publisher=Nova štamparija Davidović}}</ref> He finished primary school in Vranje, gymnasium in Vranje and [[Niš]], and the [[University of Belgrade|Great School in Belgrade]] at the History and Philology faculty.{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}} He received his Philosophy doctorate at the [[University of Vienna]] in 1898.{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}} As an official of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs he served from 1898 to 1904 in Bitola, Skopje and Belgrade.{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}} After he left the civil service in 1904, he was the secretary of the [[Society of Saint Sava]] until 1940.{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}} Throughout his life he worked for the national enlightenment of Serbs in the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}} He participated in the [[Balkan Wars]] and the [[First World War]].{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}} He retreated with the Second Morava Division [[Serbian army's retreat through Albania|through Albania]], which he described.<ref name=biblioteke/> Hadži-Vasiljević wrote extensively on history, geography and ethnology. The high value of his work is due to the basis on field research, especially in the areas of [[Old Serbia]] and [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]] (South Serbia).{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}} He wrote over 200 historical and ethnographical works about those regions.<ref name=biblioteke/> He was the editor of the ''Brastvo'' journal of the Society of Saint Sava.{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}}

==Work==
Among his most notable works are:{{sfn|National Library of Serbia}}
*Prilep i njegova okolina, Beograd, 1902;
*Južna Stara Srbija, istorijska, etnografska i politička istraživanja I–II, Beograd, 1909, 1913;
*Bugarska zverstva u Vranju i okolini 1915-1918, Novi Sad, 1922;
*Četnička akcija u Staroj Srbiji i Maćedoniji, Beograd, 1928;
*Skoplje i njegova okolina, Beograd, 1930;
*Autobiografija, Vranje

==Legacy==
A street is named after him in Vranje.<ref>http://www.vranjske.co.rs/2011-11-24/%D0%B2%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%9A%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%86-%D0%BA%D0%B0%D0%BE-%D1%81%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%86.html</ref> A bust was erected in the City Park of Vranje on 1 October 2012, at the 100th anniversary of the liberation of southern Serbia.<ref>http://www.juznevesti.com/Drushtvo/Otkrivena-bista-Jovanu-Hadzi-Vasiljevicu.sr.html</ref><ref>http://www.vranje.org.rs/vest.php?id=2714&oblast=vesti</ref>

